var RECIPE_ADJUNCT_PAIRINGS={"r1":{"intro":"A Traditional is a blank canvas — every adjunct below turns it into a melomel (fruit) or metheglin (spice). Add one and the honey shares the stage; add none and it stays a pure show mead. Start with vanilla or oak — the two highest-reward, lowest-risk upgrades.","items":[{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"½–1 split bean / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–4 wks","effect":"The classic first upgrade. Rounds a thin honey, adds a custard/marshmallow sweetness the palate reads as 'sweeter' without any added sugar. Mexican bean = bolder, Madagascar = creamier."},{"name":"Oak cubes (medium toast)","cat":"wood","dose":"15–20 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–6 wks, taste weekly","effect":"Vanilla-coconut-baking-spice plus light tannin grip; instantly reads as 'barrel-aged' and tames hot young alcohol. Pull the moment it tastes right — over-oaking is permanent."},{"name":"Citrus zest (orange/lemon)","cat":"other","dose":"zest of 1–2 fruit / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 days only","effect":"Lifts a flat honey with a fresh aromatic top note. Zest only — the white pith is bitter. Short contact; it fades, so add near bottling."},{"name":"Black tea / grape tannin","cat":"tannin","dose":"1 mug strong tea OR ¼ tsp tannin","timing":"primary","effect":"Pure structure. A thin honey mead can taste flabby and sweet-without-backbone; tannin adds the astringent 'grip' that makes it taste like a finished wine."},{"name":"Cinnamon stick","cat":"spice","dose":"1 stick / 5 L","timing":"secondary 5–10 days","effect":"Nudges it toward a light metheglin — warming, autumnal. Ceylon is gentle/floral, cassia is hot/spicy. Taste daily; cinnamon climbs fast."}],"caution":"Because a Traditional has nothing to hide behind, adjuncts show loudly — under-dose by half versus a fruit-forward recipe and build up."},"r2":{"intro":"Already an apple + cinnamon cyser, so think layering, not founding. Warm baking spices push it toward apple pie; oak pushes it toward barrel-aged farmhouse cider.","items":[{"name":"Clove (whole)","cat":"spice","dose":"1–2 cloves / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–7 days","effect":"The 'apple pie' note. Ferociously dominant — 2 cloves is plenty for 5 L; over-clove tastes medicinal/dental."},{"name":"Nutmeg + allspice","cat":"spice","dose":"pinch fresh-grated each","timing":"secondary 5–10 days","effect":"Completes the mulling-spice trio with cinnamon. Nutmeg = warm/nutty, allspice = clove-pepper-cinnamon in one. Grate fresh; pre-ground goes dusty."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1 split bean / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–4 wks","effect":"Turns sharp cider into baked apple with cream — bridges the apple and cinnamon and softens any tartness."},{"name":"Fresh ginger","cat":"spice","dose":"10–20 g sliced / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–7 days","effect":"Adds a warming bite that cuts the cyser's sweetness and lengthens the finish — apple-ginger is a natural pair."},{"name":"Oak cubes","cat":"wood","dose":"15–20 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 wks","effect":"Barrel-aged farmhouse cider; tannin balances the apple sugar and adds a dry, woody backbone."}]},"r3":{"intro":"Strawberry is delicate and FADES badly in primary (colour drops to brown-pink, aroma thins). The headline move is a secondary strawberry charge to rescue both. Everything else supports that fragile fruit.","items":[{"name":"Strawberry (secondary)","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.5–1 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Rescues the colour and fresh-jam aroma that primary fermentation strips out. Stabilize (sorbate + sulfite) first or it re-ferments and you're back to square one."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"½–1 bean / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–4 wks","effect":"Strawberries-and-cream — the definitive strawberry-mead pairing. Rounds the tartness into dessert."},{"name":"Rhubarb","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.3–0.5 kg / 5 L","timing":"primary or secondary","effect":"Adds tartness and a 'pie' savoury edge that balances strawberry's candied sweetness; also lends pink colour."},{"name":"Black pepper","cat":"spice","dose":"2–3 cracks / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 days","effect":"Chef's trick: a whisper of pepper amplifies perceived strawberry intensity. Microdose — you should never taste 'pepper', only louder strawberry."},{"name":"Hibiscus","cat":"floral","dose":"5–10 g dried / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 days","effect":"Rescues a pale batch with vivid red and a cranberry-tart lift that props up faded strawberry."}],"caution":"Avoid oak and heavy spice here — they bury strawberry, the most fragile fruit in the lineup."},"r4":{"intro":"A mixed-berry melomel already carries colour, tannin and acid, so it takes adjuncts gracefully. Oak and elderberry push it toward a serious dry fruit wine; vanilla and warm spice push it toward winter mulled berries.","items":[{"name":"Oak cubes (medium/heavy)","cat":"wood","dose":"20–25 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–6 wks","effect":"The single best upgrade — berry + oak reads as 'Bordeaux'. Adds structure, dries the finish, and lets the mead age into something wine-serious."},{"name":"Elderberry","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.2–0.4 kg / 5 L","timing":"primary or secondary","effect":"Deepens the colour to inky purple and adds grippy tannin and a dry, vinous edge. Must be cooked/dried (raw elderberry is harsh)."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1 bean / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–4 wks","effect":"Rounds the berry tartness into a jammy, pie-filling sweetness without adding sugar."},{"name":"Secondary berry charge","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.5–1 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Restores the fresh-picked aroma and colour that primary fermentation fades. Stabilize first to keep it sweet."},{"name":"Cinnamon + clove (light)","cat":"spice","dose":"1 stick + 1 clove / 5 L","timing":"secondary 5–7 days","effect":"The 'mulled winter berry' version — cozy, festive, gift-worthy. Keep the clove to one."}]},"r5":{"intro":"Blueberry has gorgeous colour but very LOW acid, so a straight blueberry mead tastes flabby and one-note. The priority adjuncts are acid and tannin to give it spine; lavender and vanilla make it a dessert.","items":[{"name":"Acid blend / lemon","cat":"tannin","dose":"½ tsp acid blend OR zest+juice of 1 lemon","timing":"secondary, to taste","effect":"Non-negotiable for blueberry — it has almost no acid of its own, so without this the mead is sweet and lifeless. Brightens everything."},{"name":"Oak cubes","cat":"wood","dose":"15–20 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 wks","effect":"Adds the structure blueberry lacks; 'blueberry wine' depth and a drier finish."},{"name":"Lavender","cat":"floral","dose":"3–5 g dried / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 days","effect":"Blueberry-lavender is a celebrated pairing — the floral lifts blueberry's muddy sweetness. Dose light; lavender turns soapy fast."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1 bean / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–4 wks","effect":"Blueberry-muffin / cobbler character; rounds the fruit and adds bakery warmth."},{"name":"Cinnamon","cat":"spice","dose":"1 stick / 5 L","timing":"secondary 5–7 days","effect":"Pushes it to blueberry cobbler — warm and homey."}],"caution":"Without added acid, blueberry mead almost always disappoints. Fix the acid before reaching for anything else."},"r6":{"intro":"Cherry is the most adjunct-friendly fruit in the book — it pairs with oak, chocolate, almond and vanilla, each pulling it toward a famous dessert. Sweet vs sour cherry sets your baseline tartness.","items":[{"name":"Oak cubes","cat":"wood","dose":"20 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–6 wks","effect":"Cherry + oak = clafoutis / Black Forest. Adds tannin and a kirsch-like depth; the most natural cherry partner."},{"name":"Cacao nibs","cat":"other","dose":"40–60 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 1–2 wks","effect":"Black Forest gateau in a glass — chocolate-cherry. Nibs (not powder) give clean cocoa without sludge; taste often, chocolate can turn bitter."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1 bean / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–4 wks","effect":"With the cacao it completes the Black Forest trio; alone it makes cherry taste like cherry-vanilla ice cream."},{"name":"Toasted almond / almond extract","cat":"other","dose":"30 g toasted slivers OR 2–3 drops extract","timing":"secondary 1–2 wks","effect":"Cherry-almond = amaretto / frangipane. Extract is potent — drops, not spoons."},{"name":"Cinnamon","cat":"spice","dose":"1 stick / 5 L","timing":"secondary 5–7 days","effect":"Warm-spiced cherry, toward a mulled / pie direction."}]},"r7":{"intro":"Already a spice metheglin, so adjuncts here are about depth and balance, not adding more heat. Vanilla and dark fruit round the spice; citrus opens it into mulled-wine territory.","items":[{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1 bean / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–4 wks","effect":"Rounds and softens an aggressive spice blend — the 'baked' note that ties cinnamon, clove and ginger together."},{"name":"Orange zest + clove","cat":"other","dose":"zest of 1 orange + 2 cloves","timing":"secondary 5–7 days","effect":"Instant mulled-wine / wassail character — festive and aromatic."},{"name":"Dried fruit (raisin/fig)","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.2–0.3 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Adds body and a dark, raisiny dessert depth that carries the spice; nudges it toward a spiced sack."},{"name":"Oak cubes","cat":"wood","dose":"15–20 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 wks","effect":"Adds woody depth and tannin so the spice has structure to sit on."},{"name":"Fresh ginger","cat":"spice","dose":"10–15 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–7 days","effect":"Sharpens the finish with a warming bite if the blend feels flat."}]},"r8":{"intro":"A heavy sweet sack has lots of residual sugar, so the job of every adjunct is to add COUNTERWEIGHT — structure and complexity that keep the sweetness from cloying. Oak is almost mandatory here.","items":[{"name":"Oak cubes (heavy toast)","cat":"wood","dose":"25–30 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–8 wks","effect":"Near-essential for a sack. Tannin balances the residual sweetness and the toast adds the caramel/vanilla complexity a big sweet mead needs to feel finished rather than syrupy."},{"name":"Dried fruit (raisin/date/fig)","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.3–0.5 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Pushes it toward port / PX sherry — sticky dark-fruit depth that suits the weight."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1–2 beans / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–4 wks","effect":"Amplifies the dessert richness; a sack can carry a double dose where a dry mead couldn't."},{"name":"Warm spice (cinnamon/clove)","cat":"spice","dose":"1 stick + 1 clove / 5 L","timing":"secondary 5–10 days","effect":"Mulled-dessert direction; the sweetness gives the spice a cushion."},{"name":"Brandy-soaked oak","cat":"wood","dose":"20 g cubes soaked in brandy","timing":"secondary 3–6 wks","effect":"Fortified-dessert character without actually fortifying — boozy warmth and barrel depth."}]},"r9":{"intro":"Bochet's caramelised honey already tastes of toffee, marshmallow and dark sugar — adjuncts that echo a dessert (vanilla, oak, dark fruit, coffee, cacao) amplify it; bright fruit fights it and is usually wasted.","items":[{"name":"Oak cubes (heavy / bourbon)","cat":"wood","dose":"25 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–8 wks","effect":"Huge synergy — caramel + bourbon-barrel = the classic bochet. Soak the cubes in bourbon for an even bigger toffee-whiskey result."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1–2 beans / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–4 wks","effect":"Amplifies the toffee/marshmallow note already present; pure dessert."},{"name":"Dark fruit (fig/date/raisin)","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.3–0.5 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Sticky-toffee-pudding character — the dried fruit and caramel reinforce each other."},{"name":"Cacao nibs","cat":"other","dose":"40–60 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 1–2 wks","effect":"Chocolate-caramel; pairs with the bochet's roast like a salted-caramel brownie."},{"name":"Cinnamon + clove","cat":"spice","dose":"1 stick + 1 clove","timing":"secondary 5–10 days","effect":"Spiced-caramel / praline; warming and festive."}],"caution":"Skip delicate fruit and florals — the deep caramel will steamroll strawberry, lavender or peach."},"r10":{"intro":"An apple cyser is endlessly spiceable. Warm baking spices make it apple pie; oak and ginger make it a grown-up farmhouse cider.","items":[{"name":"Cinnamon + clove + nutmeg","cat":"spice","dose":"1 stick + 1 clove + pinch / 5 L","timing":"secondary 5–10 days","effect":"The mulled-cider trio. Cinnamon leads, clove and nutmeg support — keep clove to one or it dominates."},{"name":"Oak cubes","cat":"wood","dose":"15–20 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 wks","effect":"Barrel-aged cider; tannin balances apple sugar and adds a dry woody backbone."},{"name":"Fresh ginger","cat":"spice","dose":"15–25 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–7 days","effect":"Apple-ginger zing — cuts sweetness, lengthens the finish."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1 bean / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–4 wks","effect":"Caramel-apple / tarte-tatin warmth."},{"name":"Star anise","cat":"spice","dose":"½–1 pod / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–6 days","effect":"A licorice-y depth that reads as 'spiced cider'. Tiny amounts — anise is invasive."}]},"r11":{"intro":"A grape pyment is the most wine-like mead, so it takes wine adjuncts best: oak, grape tannin and red-fruit all push it further toward a serious table wine.","items":[{"name":"Oak cubes","cat":"wood","dose":"20–25 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–8 wks","effect":"The most oak-appropriate recipe in the book — this is literally how wine is made. French oak = subtle/spicy, American = bold vanilla-coconut."},{"name":"Grape tannin","cat":"tannin","dose":"¼–½ tsp / 5 L","timing":"primary or secondary","effect":"Adds the structural grip of a real red; makes a thin pyment taste like a proper dry wine."},{"name":"Elderberry","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.2–0.3 kg / 5 L","timing":"primary","effect":"Deepens a red pyment's colour and tannin — a traditional way to bulk up light grape musts."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1 bean / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–4 wks","effect":"With oak gives an 'oaked Chardonnay/Rioja' creaminess."},{"name":"Blackberry","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.5 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Layers a dark-fruit jamminess over the grape — toward a fruit-forward New World red."}]},"r12":{"intro":"A braggot is half beer, so it borrows the entire brewer's adjunct shelf: hops, roast malt, coffee and oak each map it onto a known beer style.","items":[{"name":"Hops (dry-hop)","cat":"other","dose":"10–25 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–7 days","effect":"IPA-braggot — citrus/pine/tropical aroma. Cold dry-hop, short contact (over 7 days = grassy). Citra/Mosaic for tropical, Cascade for classic C-hop."},{"name":"Roast malt / cacao nibs","cat":"other","dose":"steeped roast grain OR 50 g nibs","timing":"secondary 1–2 wks","effect":"Stout-braggot — chocolate, coffee, roast. Cacao nibs are the cheat code for clean roast without re-mashing."},{"name":"Coffee (cold brew)","cat":"other","dose":"100–200 ml cold brew / 5 L","timing":"secondary, to taste","effect":"Coffee-stout braggot; add to taste at the end so it doesn't go stale or sour."},{"name":"Orange peel + coriander","cat":"spice","dose":"zest of 1 + ½ tsp crushed coriander","timing":"secondary 5–7 days","effect":"Witbier-braggot — bright, spritzy, summery."},{"name":"Oak cubes","cat":"wood","dose":"20 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–6 wks","effect":"Barrel-aged barleywine direction — deep, boozy, vanilla-oak."}]},"r13":{"intro":"Raspberry is aromatic but fades in primary like all berries. A secondary raspberry charge keeps it vivid; chocolate, rose and lime each take it somewhere distinct.","items":[{"name":"Raspberry (secondary)","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.5–1 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Restores the bright pink and fresh-raspberry nose that primary fermentation strips. Stabilize first to keep it from re-fermenting."},{"name":"Cacao nibs","cat":"other","dose":"40–60 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 1–2 wks","effect":"Raspberry-chocolate — a dessert classic; the cocoa rounds raspberry's tartness."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1 bean / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–4 wks","effect":"Raspberries-and-cream; softens the sharp acid."},{"name":"Rose petals","cat":"floral","dose":"5–10 g dried / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–6 days","effect":"Raspberry-rose — a perfumed, Turkish-delight elegance. Dose light."},{"name":"Lime/lemon zest","cat":"other","dose":"zest of 1 / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 days","effect":"Sharpens and brightens; raspberry-lime is zippy and fresh."}]},"r14":{"intro":"Blackcurrant (cassis) is intensely tart and tannic — almost too much on its own. Adjuncts here mostly TAME and round it: oak and vanilla soften the attack, star anise is the traditional partner.","items":[{"name":"Oak cubes","cat":"wood","dose":"20–25 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–8 wks","effect":"Big synergy — cassis + oak = crème-de-cassis-meets-Cabernet. Tannin and time round the ferocious acidity into something age-worthy."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1–2 beans / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–4 wks","effect":"Crucial softener — vanilla's sweetness blunts blackcurrant's sharp edge and adds a dessert roundness."},{"name":"Star anise","cat":"spice","dose":"½–1 pod / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–6 days","effect":"The classic cassis partner — a licorice depth that makes blackcurrant taste 'finished'. A little goes far."},{"name":"Secondary blackcurrant","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.5 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Restores colour and the fresh blackcurrant-leaf aroma; stabilize first so the residual sweetness survives to balance the acid."},{"name":"Cinnamon / mixed spice","cat":"spice","dose":"1 stick / 5 L","timing":"secondary 5–7 days","effect":"Winter-cassis — warm and mulled; the spice cushions the tartness."}],"caution":"Blackcurrant's acid is the whole challenge — almost every good adjunct here works by softening it, so taste for balance, not just flavour."},"r15":{"intro":"Peach has a glorious aroma that almost entirely VANISHES in primary — the headline move is always a secondary peach addition. Stone-fruit and vanilla deepen it; ginger and thyme brighten it.","items":[{"name":"Peach (secondary)","cat":"fruit","dose":"1–1.5 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Essential — primary peach ferments to a vague sweetness with no peach nose. The secondary charge is where the aroma actually comes from. Stabilize first."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1 bean / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–4 wks","effect":"Peaches-and-cream — the natural partner; rounds and enriches."},{"name":"Fresh ginger","cat":"spice","dose":"10–20 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–7 days","effect":"Peach-ginger — bright, slightly spicy, very refreshing; cuts the sweetness."},{"name":"Apricot","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.3–0.5 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Layers stone-fruit complexity; apricot's tartness props up peach's softness."},{"name":"Lemon thyme","cat":"floral","dose":"3–5 sprigs / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–4 days","effect":"A savoury-bright herbal lift — peach-thyme is a sophisticated, food-friendly twist."}],"caution":"Skip oak and heavy spice — peach is delicate and easily buried; this fruit wants support, not competition."},"r16":{"intro":"A vanilla metheglin is already a dessert base. Adjuncts here build a flavour 'shake': oak, cacao, coffee and cinnamon each pair with vanilla into a recognizable treat.","items":[{"name":"Oak cubes (bourbon-soaked)","cat":"wood","dose":"20 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–6 wks","effect":"Vanilla + bourbon-oak = cream soda / bourbon-vanilla. The single best vanilla partner."},{"name":"Cacao nibs","cat":"other","dose":"50 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 1–2 wks","effect":"Vanilla-chocolate; like a melted chocolate-vanilla swirl."},{"name":"Coffee (cold brew)","cat":"other","dose":"100 ml / 5 L","timing":"secondary, to taste","effect":"Vanilla latte — add at the end to taste."},{"name":"Cinnamon","cat":"spice","dose":"1 stick / 5 L","timing":"secondary 5–7 days","effect":"Horchata / French-toast character — warm and milky-sweet in feel."},{"name":"Toasted oak + caramel honey","cat":"wood","dose":"20 g toast cubes","timing":"secondary 3–5 wks","effect":"Cream-soda / butterscotch direction; deepens the vanilla into toffee."}]},"r17":{"intro":"A ginger metheglin wants brightness and contrast. Citrus and pear lift it; chili and turmeric deepen the warming, golden character.","items":[{"name":"Lemon / lime","cat":"other","dose":"zest + juice of 1–2 / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 days","effect":"Ginger-citrus = a Moscow-mule profile; the acid sharpens ginger's bite and adds zip."},{"name":"Pear","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.5–1 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Ginger-pear is elegant and slightly floral; pear's softness balances ginger's heat."},{"name":"Turmeric","cat":"spice","dose":"2–4 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–6 days","effect":"Golden colour and an earthy, almost medicinal depth — 'wellness tonic' character. Microdose; it stains and turns bitter."},{"name":"Chili","cat":"spice","dose":"¼–½ small chili / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–4 days","effect":"Ginger-chili double heat — warming and bold. Fruity chili (fresno) over pure-hot."},{"name":"Green tea","cat":"tannin","dose":"1 mug strong / 5 L","timing":"secondary","effect":"Adds tannin and a grassy brightness that keeps ginger from feeling heavy."}]},"r18":{"intro":"Hibiscus brings vivid red and a cranberry-tartness but little else, so adjuncts add the body and warmth it lacks. Citrus, ginger and cinnamon map it onto classic agua-de-jamaica flavours.","items":[{"name":"Citrus zest","cat":"other","dose":"zest of 1–2 / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 days","effect":"Brightens hibiscus's tart-floral into something lively and refreshing — orange or lime both work."},{"name":"Fresh ginger","cat":"spice","dose":"15–20 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–7 days","effect":"Hibiscus-ginger agua fresca; the warmth fills out hibiscus's thin middle."},{"name":"Cinnamon","cat":"spice","dose":"1 stick / 5 L","timing":"secondary 5–7 days","effect":"Agua de Jamaica — the traditional Mexican hibiscus-cinnamon pairing; cozy and aromatic."},{"name":"Raspberry / berry","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.5 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Reinforces the red colour and adds the fruit body hibiscus lacks on its own."},{"name":"Rosehip / rose","cat":"floral","dose":"5–10 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–6 days","effect":"Deepens the floral-tart layering toward a fuller, more perfumed cup."}]},"r19":{"intro":"A rose rhodomel is perfumed and delicate. The best partners are fruits and spices that share its aromatic register — lychee, raspberry, cardamom — without overpowering it.","items":[{"name":"Lychee","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.5–1 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Rose-lychee is the definitive pairing — a Gewürztraminer-like floral-tropical elegance."},{"name":"Raspberry","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.5 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Rose-raspberry — Turkish-delight character; the fruit gives the floral some flesh."},{"name":"Cardamom","cat":"spice","dose":"2–4 pods crushed / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–6 days","effect":"Rose-cardamom — Persian/Indian sweet-shop aromatics; sophisticated and warm."},{"name":"Strawberry","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.5–1 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Rose-strawberry is soft, romantic and summery."},{"name":"Saffron","cat":"spice","dose":"small pinch / 5 L","timing":"secondary 5–7 days","effect":"Luxe, honeyed, golden — rose-saffron is opulent. A few threads only; saffron is potent and pricey."}],"caution":"Rose turns soapy/potpourri if over-dosed — keep the rose light and let the partner fruit carry volume."},"r20":{"intro":"A dry-hopped mead borrows the IPA toolkit. Citrus and tropical fruit amplify the hops' own aromatics; a second hop variety layers complexity.","items":[{"name":"Citrus zest (grapefruit/orange)","cat":"other","dose":"zest of 1–2 / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 days","effect":"Amplifies the hop's natural citrus; grapefruit also boosts the perceived bitterness for a true IPA snap."},{"name":"Second hop variety","cat":"other","dose":"10–20 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–7 days","effect":"Layered dry-hopping — e.g. Citra for tropical over Cascade for grapefruit. Short, cold contact to avoid grassiness."},{"name":"Passionfruit / mango","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.4–0.7 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Hazy-IPA / tropical-pale character — the fruit and the hop thiols reinforce each other into juicy tropical."},{"name":"Spruce / pine tips","cat":"other","dose":"small handful / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–6 days","effect":"Resinous, foresty, 'fresh-cut Christmas tree' — pairs with piney hops for a wild, herbal mead."},{"name":"Lime","cat":"other","dose":"zest + juice of 1 / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 days","effect":"Sharpens and freshens — gose-adjacent when paired with a touch of salt."}]},"r21":{"intro":"A capsicumel lives on the sweet-then-heat tension. Tropical fruit and lime push the sweet/bright side; cacao and cinnamon push the deep mole side; smoke adds a savoury dimension.","items":[{"name":"Mango / pineapple","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.5–1 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Tropical sweetness is the perfect foil for chili heat — sweet-then-burn, the signature capsicumel arc."},{"name":"Lime","cat":"other","dose":"zest + juice of 1–2 / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 days","effect":"Brightens and adds the acid that makes the heat 'pop' cleanly rather than sitting heavy."},{"name":"Cacao nibs","cat":"other","dose":"50 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 1–2 wks","effect":"Chocolate-chili mole; the cocoa deepens and lengthens the heat into something rich."},{"name":"Cinnamon","cat":"spice","dose":"1 stick / 5 L","timing":"secondary 5–7 days","effect":"Mexican-chocolate / abuelita character when paired with the cacao; warm and rounded."},{"name":"Smoked / chipotle chili","cat":"spice","dose":"½ chili / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–4 days","effect":"Adds a savoury smoke layer over the heat — barbecue-adjacent, great with food."}],"caution":"Heat builds in the bottle over weeks — dose chili conservatively and taste often; you can't dial it back."},"r22":{"intro":"A coffee mead is a dessert-in-progress. Cacao, vanilla and spice each map it to a café drink; oak takes it barrel-aged-stout.","items":[{"name":"Cacao nibs","cat":"other","dose":"50–60 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 1–2 wks","effect":"Mocha — the obvious and excellent partner. Nibs give clean cocoa; taste so it doesn't turn bitter."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1 bean / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–4 wks","effect":"Vanilla latte; rounds coffee's acidity and bitterness into something smooth."},{"name":"Cinnamon + cardamom","cat":"spice","dose":"1 stick + 2 pods / 5 L","timing":"secondary 5–7 days","effect":"Turkish / spiced-coffee aromatics — exotic and warming."},{"name":"Hazelnut","cat":"other","dose":"30–40 g toasted / 5 L","timing":"secondary 1–2 wks","effect":"Nutty-coffee — a Nutella / praline-latte direction."},{"name":"Oak (bourbon-soaked)","cat":"wood","dose":"20 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–6 wks","effect":"Barrel-aged-coffee-stout depth; bourbon-vanilla-oak loves coffee."}]},"r23":{"intro":"Lavender is gorgeous but dances on the edge of soapy/potpourri — so the best adjuncts are BRIGHTENERS (lemon, bergamot) that keep it lifted, plus partners (blueberry, vanilla) that give it a sweet anchor.","items":[{"name":"Lemon zest","cat":"other","dose":"zest of 1–2 / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 days","effect":"The essential lavender partner — citrus acid cuts the soapiness and keeps the floral bright and food-friendly. Lavender-lemon is the safe, beloved combo."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1 bean / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–4 wks","effect":"Lavender shortbread — vanilla's sweetness anchors the floral and makes it dessert-like."},{"name":"Blueberry","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.5–1 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Lavender-blueberry is a celebrated pairing; the fruit gives the floral body and a jammy depth."},{"name":"Earl Grey / bergamot","cat":"floral","dose":"1 tea bag OR few drops bergamot","timing":"secondary 2–4 days","effect":"Amplifies the floral-citrus register into a perfumed, elegant 'London fog' character."},{"name":"Chamomile / elderflower","cat":"floral","dose":"3–5 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–4 days","effect":"Layered florals — softer and more honeyed; keep total floral load modest."}],"caution":"Lavender is the easiest flavour in the book to overdo. Dose at HALF what feels right, taste daily, and pull early — soapiness is permanent."},"r24":{"intro":"A chai metheglin is a spice symphony already, so adjuncts add roundness and authenticity rather than new spices. Vanilla and black tea are the two highest-value additions.","items":[{"name":"Black tea","cat":"tannin","dose":"2–3 bags strong / 5 L","timing":"secondary 1–2 days","effect":"Authentic chai needs tea tannin — it adds the astringent 'brewed' backbone that ties the spices together. Don't over-steep (bitter)."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1–2 beans / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–4 wks","effect":"Chai-latte roundness — vanilla softens the spice attack and adds the creamy sweetness chai expects."},{"name":"Extra cardamom","cat":"spice","dose":"3–4 pods / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–6 days","effect":"If the blend feels flat, cardamom is the soul of chai — bumps the aromatic top note."},{"name":"Fresh ginger","cat":"spice","dose":"15–20 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–7 days","effect":"Adds the warming bite of a proper masala chai; sharpens the finish."},{"name":"Orange zest","cat":"other","dose":"zest of 1 / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 days","effect":"A bright top note that lifts the heavy spice; spiced-orange direction."}]},"r25":{"intro":"A ruby-port-style sack is built for dark fruit and oak — the sweetness and weight demand counterweight and depth. Treat it like you're aging a young Port.","items":[{"name":"Oak cubes (heavy toast)","cat":"wood","dose":"25–30 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 6–10 wks","effect":"Essential for the port style; long oak gives the tannin and barrel depth that turns sweet mead into 'port'."},{"name":"Dark fruit (fig/plum/blackberry)","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.4–0.6 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"The ruby-port fruit core — figgy, plummy, jammy depth that carries the sweetness."},{"name":"Elderberry","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.3 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary","effect":"Deepens the ruby colour and adds the grippy tannin a port needs."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1–2 beans / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–4 wks","effect":"Rounds the whole into a smooth, dessert-ready richness."},{"name":"Brandy-soaked oak","cat":"wood","dose":"20 g soaked","timing":"secondary 4–8 wks","effect":"Fortified warmth and barrel character without literally fortifying."}]},"r26":{"intro":"A tawny-port-style mead is defined by long, slightly oxidative oak aging — so the adjuncts are dried fruit and toasted nuts that echo what oxidation and time create. This is the one recipe where a little air is a feature.","items":[{"name":"Oak cubes (heavy toast)","cat":"wood","dose":"25–35 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 2–6 months","effect":"The backbone of the style. Long, generous oak gives the caramel-nutty-woody tawny character; replace cubes once mid-aging for sustained extraction."},{"name":"Dried fruit (raisin/date/prune)","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.4–0.6 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Tawny's signature is dried-fruit and caramel — raisins and dates deliver it directly."},{"name":"Toasted nuts (walnut/almond)","cat":"other","dose":"40–60 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 1–2 wks","effect":"The nutty edge real tawny gets from oxidation; toast first for depth, taste so it doesn't go rancid."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1 bean / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–4 wks","effect":"Caramel-vanilla sweetness that fuses with the oak."},{"name":"Light controlled oxidation","cat":"other","dose":"headspace + time","timing":"extended aging","effect":"Unlike every other mead, a touch of air is desirable here — it builds the rancio / nutty-caramel tawny note. Don't overdo it; aim for 'complex', not 'sherry-flawed'."}]},"r27":{"intro":"A long-aged sweet lavender metheglin needs adjuncts with staying power that won't fade over months. Light oak gives structure; vanilla and lemon keep the floral alive across the long age.","items":[{"name":"Oak cubes (light)","cat":"wood","dose":"15–20 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–8 wks","effect":"Just enough structure to carry years of aging without burying the lavender — light toast only, the floral is the star."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1–2 beans / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–4 wks","effect":"Lavender-vanilla dessert; vanilla survives long aging beautifully and anchors the floral."},{"name":"Lemon zest","cat":"other","dose":"zest of 1–2 / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–5 days","effect":"Keeps the lavender lifted and prevents it sliding into soapiness over the long age; re-brightens a tiring floral."},{"name":"Blueberry","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.5–1 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Lavender-blueberry dessert with the body to age into something jammy and rich."},{"name":"Honey backsweeten","cat":"other","dose":"to taste at bottling","timing":"post-stabilize","effect":"A sweet lavender wants its sweetness topped up after the long ferment — stabilize, then back-add honey to the dessert level you want."}]},"r28":{"intro":"Critical truth: maple SUGAR is fully fermentable, so a straight acerglyn ferments the maple flavour almost entirely AWAY. Every smart adjunct strategy here is about restoring or anchoring 'maple' — body-leaving yeast, secondary maple, and partners (oak, vanilla, pecan) that echo it.","items":[{"name":"Bourbon-soaked oak","cat":"wood","dose":"20–25 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–8 wks","effect":"The signature pairing — maple + bourbon-oak = pancakes-and-whiskey. Oak also adds the structure maple's thin body lacks."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1–2 beans / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–4 wks","effect":"Maple-vanilla; rounds and reinforces the maple's caramel side."},{"name":"Maple syrup (secondary)","cat":"other","dose":"100–250 ml grade-B / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"The key move — because primary ferments the maple out, back-adding grade-B (darker, stronger) syrup after stabilizing is how you actually get a maple-forward mead."},{"name":"Toasted pecan / walnut","cat":"other","dose":"40–60 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 1–2 wks","effect":"Maple-pecan / butter-tart character; the nuttiness is a natural maple partner. Taste so it doesn't go rancid."},{"name":"Cinnamon","cat":"spice","dose":"1 stick / 5 L","timing":"secondary 5–7 days","effect":"French-toast direction — maple-cinnamon is cozy and breakfast-y."}],"caution":"Don't expect maple flavour to survive primary on its own. Plan from the start to either leave residual sweetness (cool, body-leaving yeast) or stabilize-and-back-add maple syrup."},"r29":{"intro":"Maple bochet doubles down on caramel — both the maple and the caramelized honey are deep, dark and toffee-ish. Dessert adjuncts (oak, vanilla, dark fruit, cacao, nuts) amplify; bright fruit is wasted.","items":[{"name":"Bourbon-soaked oak","cat":"wood","dose":"25 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 4–8 wks","effect":"Maple-bourbon-caramel — a colossal, dessert-stout-in-a-wine-glass synergy with the bochet's roast."},{"name":"Vanilla bean","cat":"spice","dose":"1–2 beans / 5 L","timing":"secondary 3–4 wks","effect":"Amplifies the toffee/caramel; pure liquid dessert."},{"name":"Dark fruit (fig/date)","cat":"fruit","dose":"0.3–0.5 kg / 5 L","timing":"secondary, stabilize first","effect":"Sticky-toffee-pudding — the dried fruit and double caramel reinforce each other."},{"name":"Cacao nibs / coffee","cat":"other","dose":"50 g nibs OR 100 ml cold brew","timing":"secondary 1–2 wks","effect":"Mocha-caramel; the roast of cacao or coffee matches the bochet's burnt-sugar depth."},{"name":"Toasted pecan","cat":"other","dose":"40–60 g / 5 L","timing":"secondary 1–2 wks","effect":"Praline / butter-pecan — maple + caramel + nut is a dessert trifecta."}],"caution":"Like the acerglyn, plan to anchor the maple (cool body-leaving ferment or secondary maple) — but the caramelized honey here survives fermentation, so the mead keeps depth even if the maple itself thins."}};

var RECIPE_COMBO_NOTES={"r1":{"intro":"A Traditional is pure honey, yeast and nutrient — so these three choices ARE the recipe. Pick a row by the result you want; the honey sets the flavour, the yeast sets the dryness and how loud that flavour reads, the nutrient keeps it clean.","combos":[{"target":"Bone-dry & crisp aperitif","honey":"Acacia (delicate, floral)","yeast":"EC-1118","nutrient":"Fermaid-O (standard)","outcome":"Ferments down near 1.000 — light-bodied, sharp and wine-like. EC-1118 is neutral enough that Acacia's faint florals still survive the dry finish. Serve well chilled; drinks young."},{"target":"Off-dry floral showpiece","honey":"Orange Blossom","yeast":"K1-V1116","nutrient":"Fermaid-O (standard)","outcome":"K1V amplifies floral terpenes, so the citrus-blossom nose becomes intense and perfumed; finishes just off-dry (~1.005) with real body. This is the 'smell the honey' flagship."},{"target":"Rich semi-sweet sipper","honey":"Buckwheat or other dark honey","yeast":"D47","nutrient":"Fermaid-O (light, ferment ≤20°C)","outcome":"D47 stalls around 1.012–1.018 leaving malty-molasses sweetness and a full, glycerol-rich body. Keep it cool — D47 throws fusel/bitter notes warm. Dessert-leaning, ages well."},{"target":"Sweet, smooth crowd-pleaser","honey":"Wildflower","yeast":"71B","nutrient":"Fermaid-O, then backsweeten","outcome":"71B caps near 14% and rounds harsh young edges, ageing fast. Stabilize and backsweeten with the same honey to a medium sweetness — the easiest reliably-delicious Traditional."}]},"r4":{"intro":"Forest Fruits already brings berry tannin and acid, so the yeast decides whether you land at 'dry fruit wine' or 'jammy off-dry melomel', and the honey decides how much it backs the berries vs. competes.","combos":[{"target":"Dry & wine-like (berry Bordeaux)","honey":"Forest or Wildflower","yeast":"EC-1118","nutrient":"Fermaid-K (early doses)","outcome":"Ferments dry; EC-1118's neutrality lets the berry tannin read like a structured dry red. Add oak in secondary and it genuinely passes for a fruit Bordeaux. Needs a few months."},{"target":"Balanced fruit-forward (best all-rounder)","honey":"Wildflower","yeast":"71B","nutrient":"Fermaid-O","outcome":"71B metabolizes the berries' harsh malic acid into softer lactic, so the fruit turns rounder and smoother; finishes off-dry with the berries still bright. The sweet spot for most palates."},{"target":"Sweet jammy dessert","honey":"Buckwheat or dark honey","yeast":"D47 (≤20°C)","nutrient":"Fermaid-O (light), backsweeten with fruit","outcome":"Full body, port-adjacent jamminess. Stabilize before the secondary fruit charge. Rich and spoonable — pairs with chocolate or cheese."},{"target":"Bright & aromatic, crisp finish","honey":"Orange Blossom","yeast":"QA23","nutrient":"Fermaid-O","outcome":"QA23 lifts thiol aromatics, so the berry nose smells fresh-picked and vivid over a crisp, dry finish. The most 'aromatic' route — drink it young and cold."}]},"r6":{"intro":"Cherry's defining trait is its malic tartness and floral esters — so the yeast choice (does it soften the acid or amplify the aroma?) changes the mead more than anything. The honey mostly sets the backdrop.","combos":[{"target":"Smooth off-dry (best balance)","honey":"Wildflower","yeast":"71B","nutrient":"Fermaid-O","outcome":"71B eats cherry's sharp malic acid, turning it into a rounder, candied-cherry character; finishes off-dry and very approachable. The friendliest, most reliable cherry mead."},{"target":"Dry cherry 'wine' (kirsch-like)","honey":"Wildflower or Acacia","yeast":"EC-1118","nutrient":"Fermaid-K","outcome":"Bone-dry and tart-forward, with a stony kirsch edge. Add oak in secondary for the clafoutis note. Serious and structured — give it time to mellow."},{"target":"Black Forest dessert","honey":"Buckwheat or dark honey","yeast":"D47 (≤20°C)","nutrient":"Fermaid-O (light) + oak & cacao","outcome":"Full-bodied and sweet; D47's body carries the dessert load while oak and cacao nibs in secondary build the cherry-chocolate Black-Forest profile."},{"target":"Aromatic amplified (cherry-blossom nose)","honey":"Orange Blossom","yeast":"K1-V1116","nutrient":"Fermaid-O","outcome":"K1V amplifies cherry's floral esters into an intense cherry-blossom perfume; keep a touch of residual sweetness so the aromatics have something to sit on."}]},"r14":{"intro":"Blackcurrant is ferociously tart and tannic, so the whole game is taming it. The yeast decides how much of that acid stays sharp; the honey and residual sweetness provide the cushion. Almost no one enjoys it bone-dry young.","combos":[{"target":"Rounded off-dry (recommended)","honey":"Wildflower","yeast":"71B","nutrient":"Fermaid-O","outcome":"71B converts the brutal malic acid into softer lactic, dropping blackcurrant's harshness to a pleasant cassis tang; finishes off-dry. The best balance of intensity and drinkability."},{"target":"Crème-de-cassis dessert","honey":"Buckwheat or dark honey","yeast":"D47 (≤20°C)","nutrient":"Fermaid-O (light), backsweeten + oak","outcome":"Rich, full and sweet — the residual sugar is what tames the savage acidity into a luxurious liqueur-like cassis. Oak and time round it further. The most pleasurable route."},{"target":"Dry & structured (serious cassis wine)","honey":"Wildflower","yeast":"EC-1118","nutrient":"Fermaid-K + oak","outcome":"Bone-dry, intensely tart and tannic — a demanding, age-worthy 'cassis wine'. Needs a year-plus and food; not a quaffer."},{"target":"Bright aromatic","honey":"Linden or Orange Blossom","yeast":"QA23","nutrient":"Fermaid-O + star anise (secondary)","outcome":"QA23's thiol lift makes the blackcurrant nose explosive over a crisp finish; a pod of star anise in secondary is the classic cassis partner that makes it taste 'finished'."}]},"r23":{"intro":"Lavender lives or dies on restraint and brightness — so the yeast matters less for sugar and more for how loud it makes the floral, and the honey should support, not fight, the lavender. Keep the lavender dose light in every version.","combos":[{"target":"Delicate & dry (let lavender lead)","honey":"Acacia or Lavender honey","yeast":"EC-1118","nutrient":"Fermaid-O","outcome":"A clean, neutral, dry ferment that gets out of the way so the lavender + honey aromatics carry unmasked. Restraint is everything — this is the purest expression."},{"target":"Off-dry floral showpiece","honey":"Orange Blossom","yeast":"K1-V1116","nutrient":"Fermaid-O","outcome":"K1V amplifies floral terpenes, turning the lavender intense and perfumey over an off-dry, bodied base. Stunning — but K1V makes soapiness louder too, so dose the lavender at half and add lemon zest."},{"target":"Lavender-vanilla dessert","honey":"Wildflower","yeast":"D47 (≤20°C)","nutrient":"Fermaid-O (light) + vanilla & lemon zest","outcome":"Full and sweet, 'lavender shortbread'; D47's body suits dessert. The lemon zest is essential here — it stops the sweet floral tipping into soap."},{"target":"Crisp & bright spritz","honey":"Linden","yeast":"QA23","nutrient":"Fermaid-O + lemon","outcome":"Linden honey's minty-herbal note bridges the lavender; QA23 finishes crisp and dry for a lemon-lavender spritz character. Light and refreshing, serve cold."}]},"r28":{"intro":"The hard truth governs every row: maple sugar ferments out completely, so 'maple flavour' largely disappears unless you keep the mead sweet (cool, body-leaving yeast) or stabilize and back-add maple in secondary. The honey and yeast set the canvas; your maple strategy sets whether it actually tastes of maple.","combos":[{"target":"Maple-bourbon dessert (signature)","honey":"Wildflower or dark honey","yeast":"D47 (≤20°C)","nutrient":"Fermaid-O (light) + bourbon-soaked oak","outcome":"D47 leaves body and residual sweetness so the maple has something to cling to; bourbon-oak in secondary builds the maple-vanilla-whiskey signature. The fullest, most maple-forward result."},{"target":"Balanced off-dry (recommended)","honey":"Wildflower","yeast":"71B","nutrient":"Fermaid-O, then back-add grade-B maple","outcome":"71B rounds the edges and leaves a touch of sweetness; stabilize and back-sweeten with dark grade-B syrup to restore the maple punch primary stripped out. The most reliable maple-tasting route."},{"target":"Dry breakfast sipper","honey":"Acacia","yeast":"EC-1118","nutrient":"Fermaid-O","outcome":"Ferments bone-dry — and be warned, the maple becomes only a faint woody whisper because every gram of maple sugar is gone. Add maple in secondary + stabilize if you want it to read 'maple' at all."},{"target":"Spiced & warming (French toast)","honey":"Dark honey","yeast":"71B","nutrient":"Fermaid-O + cinnamon & pecan","outcome":"Off-dry and cozy; cinnamon and toasted pecan in secondary give a pancake/French-toast character that reinforces the maple even as the raw sugar ferments away."}]}};

// Dutch translations of the built-in recipe descriptions, keyed by recipe id.
// Used on the share page (and the label tasting fallback) when labelLocale is 'nl'.
var RECIPE_DESC_NL={
  r1:'Een pure, honinggedreven mede zonder iets te verbergen. De klassieke stijl die het karakter van je honing laat schitteren. Perfect als eerste lot.',
  r2:'Een gezellige herfstmede — geperste appel met warme kaneelkruiding. Een etiketwaardig vlaggenschip. Drinkt prachtig op elke temperatuur.',
  r36:'Aardbeiaroma is het meest delicate van de bessen — het vervaagt het snelst door een volledige gisting. Deze versie houdt het fris door eerst een zuivere traditionele basis te vergisten en daarna in de tweede gisting op de aardbeien over te hevelen. De frisste, meest geurige van de twee aardbeimeden, met een iets blekere roze tint.',
  r3:'Een delicate, prachtig roze mede. Aardbeien zijn subtiel — het resultaat is meer "vers veld" dan snoep. Jong en gekoeld drinken.',
  r35:'Dezelfde bosvruchtenmelomel, maar de bessen gaan in de TWEEDE gisting in plaats van de primaire. Je vergist eerst een zuivere traditionele basis en hevelt dan over op het fruit — zo blijft het bessenaroma helder en fris in plaats van weg te gisten, ten koste van wat kleur en body. De aromatische tegenhanger van het recept met fruit in de primaire.',
  r4:'Een rijke, complexe melomel met diep boskarakter. Braam, framboos, bosbes en zwarte bes vormen een gelaagde bessensmaak met een prachtige robijnpaarse kleur. Een pronkstuk dat het wachten waard is.',
  r38:'De frissere tegenhanger van de bosbesmede met fruit in de primaire. Een zuivere traditionele basis vergist eerst volledig en wordt dan op geplette bosbessen overgeheveld — zo blijven een frisser fruitnoot en wat meer zuur behouden, met iets minder van de diepe aardse indigo die je krijgt door het fruit volledig mee te vergisten.',
  r5:'Een diep indigoblauwe mede met geconcentreerd bosbeskarakter. Aards, licht zurig, met een verrassende diepte. Een bosbesklassieker.',
  r6:'Een diep robijnrode mede met rijk kersenkarakter — ergens tussen kersenwijn en traditionele mede. Het best met zure kersen zoals morel.',
  r7:'Een warme, complexe gekruide mede — kaneel, kruidnagel, gember, piment en een vleugje citrus. Volgens de traditie was metheglin een medicinale mede. Wij houden gewoon van de smaak.',
  r8:'De meest geduldige van de meden. Hoog honinggehalte, hoog alcohol, zoete afdronk. Vloeibaar goud voor speciale gelegenheden — verjaardagen, mijlpalen. Vraagt minstens een jaar rijping.',
  r9:'De honing wordt voor de gisting in een pot gekarameliseerd — ontwikkelt toffee, marshmallow en donkere karameltonen. Ziet eruit als ahornsiroop; smaakt als dessert in een glas. Behoort tot dezelfde familie als creme brulee.',
  r10:'Mede met appelsap in plaats van (of naast) water. Het appelkarakter blijft het best behouden wanneer het PRIMAIR wordt toegevoegd — volledig vergisten geeft een profiel tussen droge cider en mede. Gebruik ongepasteuriseerd sap zonder bewaarmiddelen (sulfietvrij).',
  r11:'Mede met druivensap — dichter bij wijn dan bij traditionele mede. Gebruik rode of witte druivensap. Tanninerijk, perfect bij eten. Het best 6-12 maanden gerijpt voor integratie.',
  r12:'Honing + mout + hop — historisch de brug tussen mede en bier. Lager alcohol, moutige body, lichte hopbitterheid. Gist snel, drinkt jong.',
  r37:'Framboos overleeft een primaire gisting al goed — maar het fruit in de tweede gisting toevoegen duwt het aroma nog verder, met een intense, bijna parfumachtige verse-frambozenneus en een levendige magenta. Een zuivere basis vergist eerst, daarna wordt op de bessen overgeheveld.',
  r13:'Frambozen behouden hun karakter door de primaire gisting — robuust genoeg om het CO₂-uitspoelen te overleven. Briljante magenta kleur, zoetzure balans. Een van de betrouwbaarste melomels.',
  r14:'Zwarte bessen zijn intens tannisch en donker. Diep paarszwarte kleur, complex aards + bessenkarakter. Een waardig antwoord op port. Rijpt goed — minstens 1 jaar om te integreren.',
  r15:'Perziken zijn delicaat — primaire gisting spoelt hun aromatiek weg. Voeg toe in de TWEEDE gisting (na de primaire) voor vers perzikkarakter. Vergist eerst een traditionele basismede en infuseer daarna.',
  r16:'Echte vanillestokken, gespleten + toegevoegd in de tweede gisting. Geeft een zachte dessertmede — vanillevla ontmoet honingwijn. Combineer met cheesecake of drink puur.',
  r17:'Gember is een van de zeldzame kruiden die BAAT heeft bij primaire gisting — robuust genoeg om het CO₂-uitspoelen te overleven en wint aan geintegreerde warmte. Krachtig, warmend, richting ontbijtkoek.',
  r18:'Gedroogde hibiscusblaadjes in de tweede gisting — geven een prachtige robijnroze kleur en een zurig, licht tannisch bloemig karakter. Doet denken aan veenbes + roos. De kleur extraheert SNEL.',
  r19:'Gedroogde rozenblaadjes in de tweede gisting — een werkelijk delicate bloemige mede. Subtiel, parfumachtig, prachtige kleur. De klassieker van de rhodomel-categorie. Overdrijf niet; over-extractie wordt zeperig.',
  r20:'Dry-hopped traditionele mede — een moderne stijl ontleend aan craftbier. Citrus- en tropische hoparomatiek zonder bitterheid. Het best jong — hoparomatiek vervaagt snel.',
  r21:'Chilipepers in de tweede gisting — voor de durvers. Combineer zoete mede met chilihitte voor de bekende zoet-dan-vuur-combinatie. Gebruik FRUITIGE chilis (habanero, fresno), niet enkel hete. Kleine hoeveelheden volstaan ruim.',
  r22:'Cold-brew-concentraat toegevoegd in de tweede gisting — geeft koffiekarakter zonder de bitterheid van warme extractie. Drinkt als een likeur. Uitstekend na het diner.',
  r23:'Culinaire lavendel toegevoegd in de tweede gisting — een delicate, parfumachtige mede die doet denken aan een Provencaalse zomer. Het moeilijkste is terughoudendheid: lavendel wordt zeperig voorbij een drempel. Minder is meer.',
  r24:'Een kruidenmix recht uit een chai-theerecept — kardemom, kaneel, gember, kruidnagel, zwarte peper — toegevoegd in de tweede gisting. Drinkt als een warme gekruide wijn. Uitstekend om in de winter van te nippen.',
  r25:'Een bewuste robijnport-hommage — hoge dichtheid, donkerbessengedreven, zoete afdronk, 14-15% vol. Pyment-basis (rode druivensap doet het zware werk) met zwarte bes en een vleugje eikenhout. Drinkt als een jonge robijnport: diep, fruitig, weelderig.',
  r26:'Een geduldsproject: bochet-basis (gekarameliseerde honing) + vijgen + langdurige eikenrijping = een tawny-port-hommage. Waar de robijnversie fruit najaagt, jaagt deze tijd na. Drinkt naar karamel, gedroogde vijg, walnoot en butterscotch na 18+ maanden.',
  r27:'Een dessertachtige sack-mede met laat toegevoegde lavendel — hoge honingdosis, ingetogen gisting, weelderige zoetheid die parfumachtige Provencaalse bloemen draagt. Drinkt als een digestief: dik, honingachtig, met lavendel die over de jaren van scherp naar geintegreerd evolueert. Een lot van 7 flessen die je bovenhaalt bij verjaardagen.',
  r28:'Honing en ahornsiroop samen vergist — de klassieke acerglyn. De ahorn voegt een rijke, houtige diepte en lichte rook toe; de honing houdt het bloemig. Drinkt als een bos in vloeibare vorm. Het best met grade A donkere ahorn (meer smaak dan grade A licht).',
  r29:'Het bos ontmoet het kampvuur. Karameliseer de honing tot diep amber (toffee, marshmallow) en vergist daarna met grade A donkere ahornsiroop. Het resultaat smaakt als ahornbourbon met een honingruggengraat — dessertsterkte, diep amber, cadeauwaardig. Lange rijping verzacht de gebrande-suikerrand tot pure karamel-ahornweelde.',
  r30:'Een kurkdroge, op fles gerijpte mede die drinkt als een honingchampagne — fijne bubbels, frisse afdronk, de honingaromatiek opgetild door de koolzuur. Volledig droog vergist met een champagnegist, daarna geprimed en gerijpt in drukbestendige flessen. De klassieke feestmede.',
  r31:'Appelsap + honing, droog vergist en op fles gerijpt tot een frisse mousserende cyser — ergens tussen een droge cider en een lichte mede. Toegankelijk, snel en een publiekslieveling. Honing rondt de appel af; de bubbels houden het levendig.',
  r32:'Een lichte, alcoholarme mousserende mede (ongeveer 6%) die je snel kunt brouwen en jong kunt drinken — denk aan een honing-"spritz". Lage dichtheid betekent een snelle, zuivere gisting; op fles gerijpt voor een verfrissende bruis. De instap-mousserende mede.',
  r33:'Een droge mousserende melomel boordevol bosvruchtenaroma — het fruit gaat in de tweede gisting zodat het bessenkarakter helder en fris overleeft, daarna op fles gerijpt tot een roze, levendige bruis. Pectine-enzym houdt het helder.',
  r34:'Een pittige mousserende gembermede — honing + verse gember droog vergist en op fles gerijpt tot een volwassen gemberbier met ruggengraat. Warmend, droog, bruisend en gevaarlijk drinkbaar. Een blijvende favoriet.'
};

